5227513164281845, -0.009411180391907692, 0.02668428048491478, 0.025689980015158653, -0.0038297956343740225, 0.021724333986639977, 0.01445205882191658, 0.0009574489085935056, 0.0010904078371822834, -0.039217106997966766, -0.01726153865456581, 0.0017010073643177748, 0.02344701997935772, -0.020036334171891212, 0.009179947897791862, -0.004627549089491367, -0.0053530423901975155, -0.042200010269880295, -0.025158144533634186, 0.017747128382325172, -0.026545541360974312, 0.02668428048491478, -0.04423486068844795, -0.0022053841967135668, 0.0012435996904969215, 0.002647617133334279, 0.006775124929845333, -0.01219753734767437, 0.01196630485355854, 0.03230324015021324, -0.028534144163131714, 0.009457427076995373, 0.0021938225254416466, 0.0004852278798352927, 0.013238085433840752, -0.02053348533809185, 0.04525228589773178, 0.024996280670166016, -0.02360888384282589, 0.011584769934415817, -0.03558674827218056, 0.017712444067001343, -0.013295894488692284, -0.02037162147462368, 0.006538111250847578, 0.0016012880951166153, -0.021689649671316147, -0.05124121904373169, 0.0007536748889833689, 0.03325129672884941, -0.006699974648654461, -0.0067115360870957375, 0.01586258038878441, 0.009364933706820011]], "input": ["\"NORMAL SELLING PRICES, ANNUAL SALES VOLUMES, AND TOTAL VARIABLE COSTS FOR DW, WM, AND TD\":\"The normal selling prices, annual sales volumes, and total variable costs for the three products are as follows: DW: Selling price per unit = $200, Material cost per unit = $70, Labour cost per unit = $50, Contribution per unit = $80, Annual sales (units) = 5,000. WM: Selling price per unit = $350, Material cost per unit = $100, Labour cost per unit = $80, Contribution per unit = $170, Annual sales (units) = 6,000. TD: Selling price per unit = $80, Material cost per unit = $50, Labour cost per unit = $40, Contribution per unit = -$10, Annual sales (units) = 1,200.\"", "\"POTENTIAL LOSS OF SALES FOR WM AND DW IF TD CEASES PRODUCTION\":\"It is estimated that 5% of the sales of WM and DW will be lost if the TD ceases to be produced.\"", "\"REDUNDANCY AND RETRAINING COSTS FOR TD LABOUR FORCE\":\"All the direct labour force currently working on the TD will be made redundant immediately if TD is ceased now, costing $6,000 in redundancy payments. If Stay Clean waits for 12 months, the existing labour force would be retained and retrained at a cost of $3,500 to enable them to produce the new washing/drying product. Recruitment and training costs of labour in 12 months' time would be $1,200 if redundancy takes place now.\"", "\"MATERIAL COST SAVINGS AND SUPPLIER DISCOUNT SCHEME\":\"Stay Clean operates a just-in-time (JIT) policy, so all material costs would be saved on the TD for 12 months if TD production ceased now. Equally, the material costs relating to the lost sales on the WM and the DW would also be saved. The material supplier has a volume-based discount scheme in place as follows: Total annual expenditure ($) 0-600,000 = 0% discount, 600,001-800,000 = 1% discount, 800,001-900,000 = 2% discount.\"", "\"SUBLET INCOME\":\"Rental income of $12,000 that Stay Clean would receive if the space currently used for TD production is sublet for 12 months.\"", "\"SUPERVISOR COST ALLOCATION\":\"The supervisor oversees the production of all three products, spending approximately 20% of his time on TD production. He would remain fully employed even if TD production ceases.\"", "\"DECISION TO CEASE TD PRODUCTION\":\"An analysis to determine whether it is financially beneficial for Stay Clean to stop producing the TD product now rather than waiting 12 months. The analysis includes various cost and revenue factors such as lost revenue, saved labor costs, lost contribution from other products, redundancy and recruitment costs, supplier payments saved, sublet income, and supervisor costs.\"", "\"PRICING STRATEGIES TO IMPROVE FINANCIAL POSITION\":\"Two pricing strategies that could be used to improve the financial position of the business in the next 12 months if TD production continues. These strategies could involve adjusting the price of TD or other products to increase revenue or market share.\"", "\"OUTSOURCING CONSIDERATIONS\":\"Two issues that Stay Clean should consider if it decides to outsource the manufacture of one of its future products. These considerations could include factors such as cost, quality control, and supply chain reliability.\"", "\"CONTRIBUTION LOST ON TD\":\"The contribution lost on the TD of 1,200 units is calculated as 1,200 units * $10 per unit = $12,000.\"", "\"LOST CONTRIBUTION FROM OTHER PRODUCTS\":\"The loss of sales of other products will cost a lost contribution of 5% of the total sales of 5,000 units at $80 each and 6,000 units at $170 each, which equals $71,000.\"", "\"CURRENT BUYING COST\":\"The current buying cost for DW, WM, and TD is $350,000, $600,000, and $60,000 respectively, totaling $1,010,000. With a 5% discount, the total gross cost is $1,063,158.\"", "\"NEW BUYING COST\":\"The new buying cost for DW, WM, and TD is $332,500, $570,000, and $0 respectively, totaling $902,500. With a 5% discount, the total gross cost is $950,000.\"", "\"COMPLEMENTARY PRICING\":\"Complementary pricing is a strategy where products that are used together are sold at a discount when purchased together. For example, buying a TD for $80 and getting a WM for $320, resulting in a positive contribution of $130.\"", "\"PRODUCT LINE PRICING\":\"Product line pricing involves offering a package price for related products, such as those used in a utility room or kitchen, to make a positive contribution on the overall deal.\"", "\"OUTSOURCING DECISION FACTORS\":\"Outsourcing decisions should consider the cost of manufacture versus buying, the reliability of the outsourcer, the quality of work, and the loss of control over the manufacturing process.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}